description:
The Copy button on assistant messages in Chat and Scene tabs appears to do nothing when clicked — text is not copied to clipboard, and there's no user-visible feedback either way.

## Root cause (likely)

`frontend/src/components/ChatTab.tsx:164-170` and `frontend/src/components/SceneTab.tsx:164-170`:

```ts
const onCopy = useCallback((message: ChatMessage) => {
  const text =
    typeof message.contentJson === 'string'
      ? message.contentJson
      : JSON.stringify(message.contentJson);
  void navigator.clipboard?.writeText(text);
}, []);
```

Three silent-failure modes:

1. `navigator.clipboard` is undefined (insecure context, Safari restrictions, etc.) → optional chain returns `undefined`, `void undefined` no-ops.
2. `writeText` rejects (document not focused, permissions policy, browser security override) → `void` discards the promise; the rejection is invisible.
3. Success — no user-visible feedback ("Copied!" flash, button state change) so the user can't tell whether it worked.

## Established pattern in the codebase

`frontend/src/components/RecoveryCodeCard.tsx:43-58` does this correctly: feature-detects `navigator.clipboard?.writeText`, awaits in a try/catch, sets `copied`/`copyFailed` state, and flashes a "Copied!" badge for 2 seconds before reverting. ChatTab/SceneTab don't do any of it.

## Drift / convergence note

`navigator.clipboard?.writeText` is now used in three places with three different shapes:
- `RecoveryCodeCard.tsx:43-58` (full pattern: feature-detect + await + flash + fail-state)
- `ChatTab.tsx:164-170` (fire-and-forget, no feedback)
- `SceneTab.tsx:164-170` (fire-and-forget, no feedback — duplicate of ChatTab)

Per the convergence theme: extract a shared hook (`useCopyToClipboard()` or equivalent) that owns the feature-detect + await + state machine, and rebuild all three consumers on it. The CopyAction primitive should also get a visual "Copied!" state — either driven by the consumer's hook output or owned internally.

## Proposed shape

```ts
// frontend/src/hooks/useCopyToClipboard.ts
export interface UseCopyToClipboardResult {
  copy: (text: string) => Promise<void>;
  status: 'idle' | 'copied' | 'failed';
}

export function useCopyToClipboard(opts?: { resetMs?: number }): UseCopyToClipboardResult {
  // owns the await + try/catch + auto-reset timeout + feature detect
}
```

CopyAction can either accept `status` as a prop (driven by the hook) or take an async onClick and own the status internally. Internal ownership keeps consumers thin and matches how RegenerateAction's disabled prop is consumer-owned today.

## Acceptance

- Copy button on Chat and Scene assistant messages writes the text to the clipboard reliably (modern browsers on localhost, dev) and shows a "Copied!" indicator for ~1.5–2s before reverting.
- Failure path (clipboard API unavailable, permission denied, focus issue) shows a "Couldn't copy" indicator; doesn't silently disappear.
- One shared hook (or equivalent utility) replaces the three duplicates; RecoveryCodeCard migrates onto it as part of the change.
- Test coverage: hook tests for success / failure / unavailable; component test asserting the indicator state transitions (idle → copied → idle).
- Storybook story for CopyAction's three visual states.

## Related

- story-editor-k1r (broader prompt-construction convergence) — different surface, same theme: consolidate before specialising.
- story-editor-3ka (retry-visual flicker) — different surface, also a follow-up to PR #90's consolidation.

Reproduction: open Chat tab, send a message, click the copy icon under the assistant reply, paste somewhere — clipboard is empty (or whatever was previously there). Same on Scene tab.
